>>29189121
>>29189106
people LOVE labels. They especially love being able to identify with a label. Give them a label and suddenly, everyone who has the same label is their best friend and they'll march head first into hell with their fellows.

The majority of humans on earth crave community, a sense of belonging, camraderie, an "in-group" to feel safe and confide in. Theres no shame in it. Its human nature.

By the same token though, these same people want to feel unique, stand out from the crowd, but not too much or else they'll stop being able to identify with their label. So they get a new one, a new label that is more specific, makes them feel rare and exotic compared to the individuals in the larger label.

What we've seen, I believe, in the new generation of lgbtq communities is a hyperfixation on labels, mostly by the terminally lonely irl. You give these loners a label they can all identify with, and or many labels they can pick and choose to "belong" to, and suddenly you have a "community" of lonely kids doing whatever it takes to justify their label, to stay in their new in-group of "friends".

Tldr: People want attention, for better or worse, and making up a special word that defines them makes them feel like they belong to something bigger than themselves.

>>29187721
if the ssris dont pan out, heres some suggestions

bupropion - a specifically 'energizing' antidepressant. emotional blunting and fatigue much less likely. anxiety effects are a dice roll-- it could lower it or it could increase it. also watch out for brain fog, its rare but creeps up slow
moclobemide - a reversible maoi inhibitor. safer than the irreversible maoi inhibitors but a bit less effective. still, a bit more effective than SSRIs and wont cause fatigue, and i believe is also less likely to cause emotional blunting. would help with anxiety too, as an ssri would
modafinil - used for sleep/fatigue disorders, and in that context is known to have anxiety as a side effect, but anecdotally i have read from multiple people that it reduced their anxiety when used for depressive fatigue.

also of course get your stuff checked-- thyroid, iron, b vitamins, anemia etc
for thyroid, specifically get a copy of the test results and make sure the results for TSH are below 4. if theyre above 4 you need to trial treatment, regardless of what the doctor says.

Goal of the thread: At the end of the day, try to write a journal entry listing positive experiences you had throughout the day, cute things you've seen, things that were nice, you get the idea.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

I'd be happy to share my simple recipe for a Neapolitan style fresh tomato sauce. It's really simple, but most people outside Italy have never had it because the other style of tomato sauce (the slow simmered kind) is more well known.

You need 1 can San Marzano DOP tomatoes (usually far better than most grocery store tomatoes), 1 bunch basil leaves, 2 cloves of garlic (diced super fine, grated or pressed), 3 tbsp olive oil, and a little salt to taste (at the end).

If you have a manual food mill, using that to grind the tomatoes is best. Otherwise you can use a food processor. Put a large saute pan on the stove on medium low, add oil plus garlic. Once the garlic begins to bubble turn head down to low. You want the garlic to cook a bit but not brown. Once garlic has cooked for a few minutes, add tomato puree and raise heat to medium-high. Once it begins to simmer rapidly, stir frequently and allow to cook for 8-10 minutes until desired consistency has been reached. Once tomatoes are cooked enough, taste for salt and adjust, and then add fresh basil sliced or torn into little pieces and killt the heat (if you expose the basil to heat for more than a minute or two it will lose all its flavor, so that's why I add lots of it right at the end).

Voila, quick, simple , easy tomato sauce that will blow away any other plain tomato sauce you've ever had.

Microneedling is sort of like minoxidil, it improves blood flow by stimulating healing and regeneration, which can regenerate hair follicles. You can try it on your hairline, it's a bit painful.
